1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,333
Welcome to the BATbern Event Management Platform!

2
00:00:10,333 --> 00:00:20,666
Today I'll show you how to plan an event without losing your mind.

3
00:00:20,666 --> 00:00:31,000
We'll walk through the complete event lifecycle, from "Oh god, we need an event" to "Finally over, into the archive it goes!" You'll see all the important steps an organizer takes to plan a Berner Architekten Treffen without panicking.

4
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:37,200
We begin at the Event Dashboard.

5
00:00:37,200 --> 00:00:43,400
This is your command center, where you keep track of all events you've ever organized or will organize.

6
00:00:43,400 --> 00:00:49,600
Authentication via AWS Cognito is already done.

7
00:00:49,600 --> 00:00:55,800
You see your username in the top right, giving you the power to use all organizer functions.

8
00:00:55,800 --> 00:01:02,000
With great power comes great responsibility!

9
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:10,500
Now we're creating a brand new event! Click the "New Event" button in the top right. Boom!

10
00:01:10,500 --> 00:01:19,000
A modal form appears. Don't worry, it looks like a lot, but we'll fill it out together.

11
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:25,333
Event number. A unique identifier for this event.

12
00:01:25,333 --> 00:01:31,666
The system internally uses the format "BATbern" followed by the number. Like a birth certificate for your event.

13
00:01:31,666 --> 00:01:38,000
This serves to identify it in the database and URLs.

14
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:45,333
Title. This is the name that should excite your participants!

15
00:01:45,333 --> 00:01:52,666
"Boring Architecture Event Number 47" would be honest, but maybe not the best choice.

16
00:01:52,666 --> 00:02:00,000
Choose something meaningful that people will see on the public website.

17
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:05,000
Description. A brief explanation of the event topic.

18
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:10,000
This information helps interested parties understand why they should definitely register.

19
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:15,000
Or at least, what it's about.

20
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:21,200
Event type.

21
00:02:21,200 --> 00:02:27,400
Choose between three formats: "Evening" for after-work events, where you can network after work.

22
00:02:27,400 --> 00:02:33,600
"Afternoon" for afternoon events, perfect for those who prefer the couch in the evening.

23
00:02:33,600 --> 00:02:39,800
Or "Full-day" for all-day conferences. You'll need lots of coffee for that!

24
00:02:39,800 --> 00:02:46,000
This influences time planning and slot management.

25
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:51,666
Date and registration deadline. The event date determines when the event takes place.

26
00:02:51,666 --> 00:02:57,332
Please choose a date in the future, we don't support time travel yet.

27
00:02:57,332 --> 00:03:03,000
The registration deadline is important for participant management.

28
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:09,333
Venue. Name and address of the event location.

29
00:03:09,333 --> 00:03:15,666
So not "my basement", but a real place with an address.

30
00:03:15,666 --> 00:03:22,000
This information will be displayed on the public website, so people can actually go there.

31
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:27,666
We click "Save" and the event is created. Tada!

32
00:03:27,666 --> 00:03:33,332
The system automatically returns to the dashboard, and there it is! Your brand new event in the list.

33
00:03:33,332 --> 00:03:39,000
Your baby is born!

34
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:45,000
After event creation, we navigate to the event detail page. Here we can assign tasks to team members.

35
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:51,000
Because why should you do everything alone when you have a whole team?

36
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:57,000
Click "Edit" to reopen the event form.

37
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:03,500
Switch to the "Tasks" tab.

38
00:04:03,500 --> 00:04:10,000
Here you see a predefined list of standard tasks that occur with every event.

39
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:16,500
The system knows its stuff, it knows what needs to be done.

40
00:04:16,500 --> 00:04:23,000
For each task, we select a responsible organizer from the dropdown menu.

41
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:29,500
This ensures all important activities are clearly assigned and nothing is forgotten.

42
00:04:29,500 --> 00:04:36,000
Because forgotten tasks lead to chaos, and chaos leads to... well, more chaos.

43
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:40,500
After assignment, we click "Save".

44
00:04:40,500 --> 00:04:45,000
The system saves all tasks and returns to the event detail page. Perfect!

45
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:51,400
To review the tasks, we navigate to the task list.

46
00:04:51,400 --> 00:04:57,800
Initially, you see the default filter "My Tasks", showing only your own tasks.

47
00:04:57,800 --> 00:05:04,200
But we're curious and want to know what the others are up to.

48
00:05:04,200 --> 00:05:10,600
We change the filter to "All Tasks" to see all assignments.

49
00:05:10,600 --> 00:05:17,000
This gives an overview of responsibilities across the team. And who might have nothing to do.

50
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:22,500
Back on the event detail page, we begin content planning! The first step is topic selection.

51
00:05:22,500 --> 00:05:28,000
Click "Select Topic".

52
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:32,333
A view opens with various topic categories.

53
00:05:32,333 --> 00:05:36,666
The default view shows a list, but we use the Heat Map for a better overview.

54
00:05:36,666 --> 00:05:41,000
Because who doesn't love a good Heat Map?

55
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:48,250
The Heat Map is a two-dimensional matrix that visualizes topics by popularity and timeliness.

56
00:05:48,250 --> 00:05:55,500
Bright colors show popular topics, the rockstars among architecture topics.

57
00:05:55,500 --> 00:06:02,750
Darker colors show less frequently chosen topics. The underdogs that also deserve a chance.

58
00:06:02,750 --> 00:06:10,000
This helps with strategic topic planning based on participant interests.

59
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:15,500
We select a topic from the Heat Map by clicking on a cell.

60
00:06:15,500 --> 00:06:21,000
The system marks the selection and displays details.

61
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:26,500
After confirmation, the system saves the selected topic and automatically opens the speaker brainstorming view.

62
00:06:26,500 --> 00:06:32,000
The system is like a good assistant, it always knows what comes next!

63
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:37,200
Now we collect potential speakers for the selected topic!

64
00:06:37,200 --> 00:06:42,400
In this phase, we create a pool of candidates we'll contact later.

65
00:06:42,400 --> 00:06:47,600
We add four speaker candidates.

66
00:06:47,600 --> 00:06:52,800
This gives us enough options for outreach, in case not everyone accepts.

67
00:06:52,800 --> 00:06:58,000
Because speakers are like cats, sometimes they just say no, for no reason.

68
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:03,666
After adding all candidates, we click "Proceed to Contact".

69
00:07:03,666 --> 00:07:09,332
The system automatically switches to the Kanban view, where we can track contact status. Kanban!

70
00:07:09,332 --> 00:07:15,000
That sounds important and organized!

71
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:22,666
We're now in the speaker contact phase.

72
00:07:22,666 --> 00:07:30,332
The Kanban board shows several columns representing the workflow.

73
00:07:30,332 --> 00:07:38,000
From "Who is this?" through "Contacted" to "Hurray, they accepted!" This visualization gives a quick overview of speaker acquisition progress.

74
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:44,000
Now we systematically contact all speaker candidates.

75
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:50,000
For each candidate, we click on the card and open the contact dialog.

76
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:56,000
This documentation is important for tracking and for other team members who need to check the status.

77
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:02,000
Otherwise, next week someone asks: "Did we contact them already?" And nobody knows. Chaos avoided!

78
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:08,000
After receiving positive responses, we move speakers through the workflow!

79
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:14,000
It's like Tetris, but with people. We use drag-and-drop to move cards between columns.

80
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:20,000
We move four speakers to the "READY" column.

81
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:26,000
In the next step, we move speakers from "READY" to "ACCEPTED".

82
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:32,000
All four READY speakers are moved to ACCEPTED. Running like clockwork!

83
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:38,666
Before speakers can submit their content, we must publish the topic.

84
00:08:38,666 --> 00:08:45,332
We navigate to the "Publication" tab and click "Publish Topic".

85
00:08:45,332 --> 00:08:52,000
In the lower area, a preview of the event on the public page is visible. Nice, right?

86
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:58,500
Back in the speakers tab, we now submit presentation content for each speaker.

87
00:08:58,500 --> 00:09:05,000
Title, abstract, the usual suspects.

88
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:11,500
We repeat this process for all three speakers with confirmed presentations. Copy, paste, repeat.

89
00:09:11,500 --> 00:09:18,000
Just kidding, each speaker has unique content of course!

90
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:23,000
After content submission comes quality review.

91
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:28,000
Now that we have the content, we can publish the speakers. We click "Publish Speakers".

92
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:33,000
And here it comes!

93
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:38,000
Now on the public website, not only the topic but also the confirmed speakers with their topics are visible.

94
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:43,000
The world can see it!

95
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:49,666
Back in the speakers tab, we now review and approve each submitted presentation.

96
00:09:49,666 --> 00:09:56,332
We're playing quality control now. Looks good, looks good, that too. We approve all three presentations.

97
00:09:56,332 --> 00:10:03,000
Green light for all!

98
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:09,000
For slot assignment, we switch to the Sessions view. Click "Manage Slot Assignments".

99
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:15,000
Now it's getting scheduled!

100
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:21,000
For quick initial planning, we use the Auto-Assign function.

101
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:27,000
The system performs automatic assignment. Magic! The system does the work.

102
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:33,000
Manual assignment is also possible here through drag-and-drop.

103
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:39,000
In case you don't trust the computer or just like moving things around.

104
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:44,000
After slot assignment, we click "Back to Event".

105
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:53,000
The final step is agenda publication! The grand finale! Click "Publish Agenda". And...

106
00:10:53,000 --> 00:11:02,000
The event is now fully planned and publicly accessible including detailed agenda! Confetti! Fireworks!

107
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:11,000
Okay, maybe just in our minds, but still! We made it!

108
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:18,000
After the event has taken place, we archive it for historical records.

109
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:25,000
Switch to the "Overview" tab and click "Edit". Time to retire the event.

110
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:34,000
In the form, select "ARCHIVED" as the status. The event was great, but now it's history.

111
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:39,666
For testing purposes, you can override the workflow validation.

112
00:11:39,666 --> 00:11:45,332
Activate the "Override Workflow Validation" checkbox and click "Save".

113
00:11:45,332 --> 00:11:51,000
This is like the emergency exit, in case things don't go according to plan.

114
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:57,750
With that, the complete event workflow is finished!

115
00:11:57,750 --> 00:12:04,500
From the first idea to the archive, we've made the whole journey together!

116
00:12:04,500 --> 00:12:11,250
You're now an event management pro! Thank you for your attention!

117
00:12:11,250 --> 00:12:18,000
And remember: Event planning is fun, at least with the right software! Goodbye! See you at the next BATbern. Geetings from the Creator Nissim.

